The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 LOOSE CHANGE

 Mutual fund houses are lowering the entry barriers for investment in their systematic investment plans to attract more retail investors. Reliance Mutual Fund has announced a reduction in its minimum SIP instalment to Rs 100 per month. ICICI Prudential followed suit with an SIP of Rs 50 per month only. Most of the fund houses have a minimum SIP instalment between Rs 500 and Rs 1,000.

 DBS Chola Hedged Equity Fund has listed at Rs 10.47 against a face value of Rs 10 per unit. The scheme was launched in March 2007. The objective of the scheme is to generate long-term capital appreciation through investment in equity and equity related instruments.

 Franklin Templeton Investments (India) has launched a capital protection oriented scheme. This is the second such fund from the house. The new fund offer is open till May 17. Its first such fund, called Franklin Templeton Capital Safety Fund, had two options a three-year maturity plan and a five-year maturity plan. 

 Indian Overseas Bank is offering a 10.25 per cent interest per annum to senior citizens if they keep aggregate deposits up to Rs 25 lakh in the same branch or different branches of the bank.




